                    "node": {
                        "created_at": "1768384319",
                        "id": "17880219501448473",
                        "text": "Save this for your Japan trip \ud83c\uddef\ud83c\uddf5\n\nThese 5 phrases will cover 80% of your daily life here, even if you know zero Japanese.\n\n1 Arigatou gozaimasu = polite thank you. Use it for literally everything: shops, trains, restaurants, hotels.\n2 Sumimasen = excuse me + sorry + \u201chi can I ask something?\u201d It\u2019s the safest way to get attention.\n3 Onegaishimasu = the\u4e07\u80fd word. It\u2019s \u201cplease\u201d but also \u201cyes, that\u2019s what I want\u201d when you\u2019re ordering or handing something over.\n4 Daijoubu desu = \u201cI\u2019m good / it\u2019s fine.\u201d Great for refusing politely. Also means \u201care you okay?\u201d so listen for it.\n5 Wakarimasen = \u201cI don\u2019t understand.\u201d Say it with a smile and people will usually slow down or switch to simple English.\n\nIn Japanese there\u2019s a \u201cpolite\u201d version (recommended for travel) and a \u201ccasual\u201d version (still fine, just more informal).\n\n1 Thank you\nPolite: arigatou gozaimasu\nCasual: arigatou\n\n2 Excuse me / sorry / to get attention\nPolite: sumimasen\nCasual: gomen / gomen ne\n\n3 Please / yes please / can you do this\nPolite: onegaishimasu\nCasual: onegai\n\n4 I\u2019m good / it\u2019s fine / no thanks\nPolite: daijoubu desu\nCasual: daijoubu\n\n5 I don\u2019t understand\nPolite: wakarimasen\nCasual: wakannai\n\nTip: if you\u2019re unsure, just use the polite one \u2014 it always lands well."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
